This is Dingo's Garage.  It's divided into two sections - a larger one and a smaller one.

In the larger section, there is a large tank, four ATV's, and a solid looking all-purpose vehicle (or SUV).  In the smaller section there are two different luxury automobiles and a motorcycle.  On the south wall, there is a massive garage door.  You could quite literally drive a plane through here.  Just to the right of the garage door is a numbered panel.

Two doors lead northwest and north, the latter looking a little older and thicker.

You freeze in fear as you hear a noise coming from the direction of the SUV.  You are definitely not alone.
> search suv

> search suv
You follow the faint scuffling sound and you peer under the SUV.  You see Blerk cowering underneath.

"Blerk," you say gently.  "It's Xan-Xan.  Let's go."

At the sound of your voice, Blerk settles a bit and scurries out from under the SUV.  Blerk hugs you fiercely and says, "'Ets go.  Hurry.  Hurry!"
> use panel

> use panel
With Blerk in the room and the vehicles in the garage disabled and Strauss ready to go, you feel confident to try entering the correct code.

You better be superconfident about this.  One wrong code and you'll likely have a swarm of Dingoes all over the garage.  (In other words, please save before continuing!  If you are unsure of the code, type 'abort', and think carefully about your password)

You walk over to the panel and enter:
A voice booms over the loud speakers, "The art of using troops is this:  If in all respects unequal, be capable of eluding him."
> D@15IN&33GO$62!
You carefully punch in D@15IN&33GO$62! and hit enter.  After a few seconds you hear the grinding of heavy gears far above you and the garage door slowly opens.
A faint beeping can be heard as the garage door rises.  Bustling sounds can be heard in the compound and a loud voice booms over the loud speaker:
"ALL MILITARY PERSONEL REPORT TO THE SOUTH GATE.  WE HAVE A BREACH!  PUNJAB, MAMOUF, HUMPERDINCK, WAZLIB, IVEBEENABAD... REPORT TO THE GARAGE FOR PURSUIT!"

"REPEAT:  "ALL MILITARY PERSONEL REPORT TO THE SOUTH GATE.  WE HAVE A BREACH!  PUNJAB, MAMOUF, HUMPERDINCK, WAZLIB, IVEBEENABAD... REPORT TO THE GARAGE FOR PURSUIT!"

Wearing Blerk like a snug fitting backpack, you hop on one of the ATVs and turn the ignition over.  Just as you do you see six people burst through the north door.  You don't waste time, but you take a close look at your pursuers:

You see:
+ a tall, thin man wearing scrubs
+ a taller, cleanly shaven man with a distinct scar above his right eye
+ a massive lady wearing an apron and carrying a heavy rolling pin
+ a shorter grimy fellow with a thick beard and sunglasses
+ the unmistakable bird-of-prey-appearance of the Sarlashkar

Behind them all is a thin, well endowed, attractive red head that you have never seen before.

Smoke rises from the garage floor as your working four wheeler squeals out of the garage.  The pursuing Dingoes scatter for their respective automobiles and you exit the compound and speed out into the hot desert air.

You tear through the open desert on your four wheeler.  A strange thicket blocks your way to the west.  Behind you, to the north, the mighty compound looms in the receding distance.  An old town blocks your progress to the south.  Your only real option is to head southwest into the open desert.
Dr. Dingo's black car seems to have made it out of the garage and is in chase.
> sw

> sw

You are in another open expanse of desert.  To your right you see the southern gates of the compound opening and armed Dingo vehicles preparing their exit.  Better hurry.  Dr. Dingo's black car is still in pursuit.

The only option you have is to continue toward the south.

You leave the compound behind you.  In the distance, off to the northeast, you hear a massive explosion that shakes the ground.  You grin, thinking that the Sarlashkar was probably in that exploding tank.

> s

> s
You continue at high speed off to the south.

You nearly are knocked off your four wheeler as an explosion rocks you from behind.  You glance over your shoulder and see pieces of the Dingo's black car flying skyward.  A ball of fiery gas and a plume of smoke consume the desert air behind you.  As ruthless at it sounds, you hope the Dingoes died slowly in the explosion.

There is some sparse vegetation here and that faint outline of a road that head to the west.
You drive for what seems like hours at high speeds into more open desert.

As you do, the four wheeler chokes and sputters and finally comes to a stop.  You step off the four wheeler.  Bummer.  Out of gas.

> w

> w
You are dead tired.  You stumble off toward the west.

You are vaguely aware of a few small 'homes' off in the distance.  The road here is a little more defined and the ground is a little less sandy.
> wait

> wait
Time passes.

You struggle to keep your wits and your bearings in this hot stifling air.  Your adventure has finally caught up to you.

You stumble a few steps toward the small village in the distance and fall exhausted, face first on to the hard dirt path.

Blerk urges you to continue.  The last thing you remember before passing out is Blerk grunting and pulling you by the arm toward the village.

You awaken, not feeling a whole lot better than you did, but at least you are alive.  You are on a small, uncomfortable cot in a shaded, thatched hut.

You open your eyes and see three small kids standing over you.  All are giggling.  One of them is gently prodding you with a blunt stick.  They laugh as you feebly swat the stick away.  You sit up and look around.

A colorfully dressed older lady sees you sit up and walks toward you.  The children part way and make room for her.  She comes over and kneels next to your cot.

"Easy child."  She takes you hand.  "You are safe now.  We will take good care of you.  Can you tell me your name, dear?"

You open your mouth to speak, but nothing comes out.  You pause.  Confused.  After a moment of silence, the lady says, "Sweetheart.  Can you tell me your name?  How did you get here?"

...
...
...

In a raspy voice, you respond,

"No."  You shake your head... "I can't remember a thing."

